{
  "texts": [
    "Edelman, Ngwe and Peng (2023) shows that self-reported time savings from AI chatbots-particularly Microsoft Copilot-may overstate actual productivity gains.",
    "This further reinforces the point that workers' productivity improvements from AI chatbots are modest, as our self-reported time savings estimates would then represent an upper bound on realized benefits.",
    "That said, overstated gains may not be the full story: Section 4.1 shows that workers' self-reported earnings effects closely align with our difference-in-differences estimates based on administrative data, reflecting that workers recognize that AI chatbots have not materially improved their earnings.",
    "This analysis of incumbent workers resembles the research designs of Autor et al. (2014); Walker (2013).",
    "Task importances are derived from our survey, which asked workers to rate the importance of six representative O*NET job tasks in their occupations; see Appendix J andHumlum and Vestergaard (2025, SI6) for details."
  ]
}